This article will teach you how to build web push notifications using Angular and ASP .NET.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

What are Push Notifications?
A push notification is a short message that appears as a pop-up in your desktop browser, on your mobile home screen, or in your mobile app's notification center. The notification is generated by the browser (or the device) and will appear regardless of what tab you’re viewing.
How do Push Notifications work on the web?
To establish a connection between parties (client and server), you need to use VAPID keys, which consist of a public and private key.
Subscription:

• The client generates a subscription using the service worker service using the public key.

• The client sends the subscription to the server.

• The server receives the request and stores it in the collection.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Notification:

• The notification usually arrives after an event (such as a newsletter post or a video upload).

• To simulate this, create a worker service that occasionally queries the subscriptions collection and invokes the Web Push API that uses Firebase Cloud Messaging (FCM).

• The WebPush protocol validates the subscription (p256dh and auth encryption) via the public key and generates a notification using the private key.

• The notification is delivered to your web browser via the service worker.

• The push notification appears in the browser.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

The Push Notifications use the HTTP2 protocol, which (unless you’re on localhost) requires an HTTPS connection between the client and the server.

VAPID
The WebPush API requires a Voluntary Application Server Identity (VAPID) control. VAPID auth consists of:

• Public key

• Private key

• Email (completely optional)
The public key is stored in the browser and on the server. The private key is stored only on the server and should not be shared. The private key is used to generate notifications.
Get VAPID keys
You can generate VAPID keys using the NPM web-push library. Initialize a Node.js project:
$ npm init -yThen, install the web-push library from NPM.
$ npm i web-pushCreate an app.js file and paste the following:
const webpush = require('web-push');// VAPID keys should be generated only once.
const vapidKeys = webpush.generateVAPIDKeys();
console.log('vapidKeys :>> ', vapidKeys);
Run an app.js file in the terminal (using Node.js), and VAPID keys will be printed in the console:
> node app.js// VAPID keys example
vapidKeys :>> {
publicKey: 'BDc...',
privateKey: 'xHt....'
}
Save the public and private keys for later.
Setting up a Service Worker in an Angular project
Creating a new Angular project
If you have Angular installed on your machine, you can create a project using the CLI:
> ng new angular-pwa-mediumThis generates an empty project. The next step is to add service worker capabilities (in the newly generated project), and that’s easily done using Angular PWA:
> ng add @angular/pwaThis command installs the @angular/service-worker package in the project and generates a couple of new files, like:

• public/manifest.webmanifest — used for cross-device synchronization

• ngsw-config.json — Angular service worker engine — enables offline capabilities, caching, push notifications, etc.
The service worker is loaded in the app.config.ts file (or app.module ), and it’s activated when not in development mode:
// app.config.ts
import { ApplicationConfig, provideBrowserGlobalErrorListeners, isDevMode } from '@angular/core';
import { provideRouter } from '@angular/router';
import { routes } from './app.routes';
import { provideServiceWorker } from '@angular/service-worker';
export const appConfig: ApplicationConfig = {
providers: [
provideBrowserGlobalErrorListeners(),
provideRouter(routes), provideServiceWorker('ngsw-worker.js', {
enabled: !isDevMode(),
registrationStrategy: 'registerWhenStable:30000'
})
]
};I’ll get back to this file later, but for the most part, you don’t have to worry about any of this stuff. It just works and requires no changes.

The important part is the SwPush service that comes with angular-pwa.
import { SwPush } from '@angular/service-worker';@Component({...})
export class AppComponent {
constructor(private readonly swPush: SwPush) { }
}
The service worker exposes a method that checks whether the browser supports a service worker:
this.swPush.isEnabled // true / falseThis is crucial, or notifications will not work.
I’ll later demonstrate how to make this work in localhost.
Another important method, requestSubscription(), generates a subscription object based on the VAPID public key:
@Component({...})
export class AppComponent implements OnInit { private PUBLIC_VAPID_KEY = 'YOUR_PUBLIC_KEY';
constructor(private readonly swPush: SwPush) { }
ngOnInit() {
from(
this.swPush.requestSubscription({
serverPublicKey: this.PUBLIC_VAPID_KEY,
})
)
.subscribe(console.log)
}
}
The requestSubscription() method returns a Promise, but I converted it to an observable to keep things consistent.
Here is what’s inside the subscription object:
{
"endpoint": "https://fcm.googleapis.com/fcm/send/<browser_instance>:<session_ID>",
"expirationTime": null,
"keys": {
"p256dh": "BC..SOME-UNIQUE-ID",
"auth": "gAe..SOME-UNIQUE-ID"
},
"options": [...]
}The interested parts are the endpoint, p256dh, and auth. These will be sent to the backend to authenticate the user and produce a notification.
Let’s start implementing notifications.
ASP.NET Web API Project
Time to shift gears to the backend. Start by installing the Web Push NuGet Package.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

<ItemGroup>
<PackageReference Include="WebPush" Version="1.0.12" />
</ItemGroup>Then, define the model that accepts the subscription object sent by Angular:
namespace WebPushAPI.Models
{
public record CreateSubscriptionRequest(
string Endpoint,
Dictionary<string, string> Keys
);
}As well as add an extension method that will map the incoming request into a PushSubscription.
using WebPush;
using WebPushAPI.Models;namespace WebPushAPI.Extensions
{
public static class PushSubscriptionExtensions
{
public static PushSubscription ToPushSubscription(this CreateSubscriptionRequest request)
{
request.Keys.TryGetValue("p256dh", out string? p256dh);
request.Keys.TryGetValue("auth", out string? auth);
return new PushSubscription // WebPush
{
Endpoint = request.Endpoint,
P256DH = p256dh,
Auth = auth
};
}
}
}
Each PushSubscription will be stored in our in-memory collection, where the key is the unique browser subscription (token) and the value is the mapped subscription.
private static readonly ConcurrentDictionary<string, PushSubscription> _subscriptions = new();Extracting Firebase Token
The endpoint parameter inside the PushSubscription consists of the Firebase URL (https://fcm.googleapis.com/fcm/send), followed by the browser instance and the session ID:
"https://fcm.googleapis.com/fcm/send/<browser_instance>:<session_ID>"e.g.,: "https://fcm.googleapis.com/fcm/send/d_A4E5V:JH31564D894D2D12TRUH"
Each browser instance gets its own stable token. The interesting part is after the URL, so split it and take the second half:
private static string ExtractFCMToken(string subscriptionEndpoint)
{
const string prefix = "https://fcm.googleapis.com/fcm/send/"; return subscriptionEndpoint.StartsWith(prefix)
? subscriptionEndpoint[prefix.Length..]
: subscriptionEndpoint;
}
// input = https://fcm.googleapis.com/fcm/send/d_A4E5V:JH31564D894D2D12TRUH
// output = d_A4E5V:JH31564D894D2D12TRUH
public bool AddSubscription(PushSubscription subscription)
{
var token = ExtractFCMToken(subscription.Endpoint); var newSub = _subscriptions.AddOrUpdate(token, subscription, (oldValue, newValue) => newValue);
return newSub is not null;
}
Later, you’ll use the same token to add or remove PushSubscription from the collection.
Building Repository
Isolate the subscription management in the SubscriptionRepository:
using WebPush;namespace WebPushAPI.Repository
{
public interface ISubscriptionsRepository
{
bool AddSubscription(PushSubscription subscription);
bool RemoveSubscription(string token);
ICollection<PushSubscription> GetAllSubscriptions();
}
}
using System.Collections.Concurrent;
using WebPush;namespace WebPushAPI.Repository
{
public class SubscriptionsRepository(ILogger<SubscriptionsRepository> logger) : ISubscriptionsRepository
{
private static readonly ConcurrentDictionary<string, PushSubscription> _subscriptions = new();
public bool AddSubscription(PushSubscription subscription)
{
var token = ExtractFCMToken(subscription.Endpoint);
var newSub = _subscriptions.AddOrUpdate(token, subscription, (oldValue, newValue) => newValue);
return newSub is not null;
}
public bool RemoveSubscription(string token)
{
var isRemoved = _subscriptions.TryRemove(token, out _);
if (!isRemoved)
{
logger.LogError("Failed to remove subscription!");
return false;
}
return true;
}
public ICollection<PushSubscription> GetAllSubscriptions()
{
return _subscriptions.Values;
}
private static string ExtractFCMToken(string subscriptionEndpoint)
{
const string prefix = "https://fcm.googleapis.com/fcm/send/";
return subscriptionEndpoint.StartsWith(prefix)
? subscriptionEndpoint[prefix.Length..]
: subscriptionEndpoint;
}
}
}
If you’re wondering why I’m using _subscriptions.AddOrUpdate() method, I explained it here.

The next step is to create REST API endpoints that receive the subscription from the Angular frontend and store it in the collection, and another that removes it.
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
using WebPushAPI.Extensions;
using WebPushAPI.Models;
using WebPushAPI.Repository;namespace WebPushAPI.Controllers
{
[Route("api/[controller]")]
[ApiController]
public class SubscriptionController(ISubscriptionsRepository repository) : ControllerBase
{
[HttpPost("Subscribe")]
public IActionResult Subscribe([FromBody] CreateSubscriptionRequest request)
{
var pushSubscription = request.ToPushSubscription();
var isAdded = repository.AddSubscription(pushSubscription);
return isAdded ?
Created(string.Empty, new { message = "Subscribed successfully!" })
: StatusCode(500, "Something went wrong!");
}
[HttpDelete("UnSubscribe/{token}")]
public IActionResult UnSubscribe([FromRoute] string token)
{
var isRemoved = repository.RemoveSubscription(token);
return isRemoved ?
Ok(new { message = "Subscription removed!" })
: StatusCode(500, "Something went wrong!");
}
}
}
With this in place, the client can subscribe and unsubscribe.
Creating Notifications
Notification model
To produce a notification, the Chrome browser expects a message in the following format:
{
"notification": {
"title": "string",
"body": "string"
}
}And in the exact case (camel case). Therefore, created the response models:
namespace WebPushAPI.Models
{
public record SendNotificationResponse(NotificationData Notification); public record NotificationData(string Title, string Body);
}
As you can tell, I’m using records instead of classes for DTOs. If you’re unfamiliar with records, you can learn more here.
Later, when I create the notification:
var notification = new NotificationData("Hello!", "This is a push notification!");
var payload = new SendNotificationResponse(notification);I’ll use the JSON Serializer to convert the model to a string, but more importantly, change property keys to camel-case:
private static readonly JsonSerializerOptions _jsonOptions = new()
{
PropertyNamingPolicy = JsonNamingPolicy.CamelCase
}; ...
// convert to json and map to camel-case (browser expects camel-case)
var jsonPayload = JsonSerializer.Serialize(response, _jsonOptions);
